    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:6cb14b5e-d07e-4cd8-91e4-71ba6d0e3671",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 13-year-old girl who arrives looking alert but visibly tense, often twisting the sleeve of her sweatshirt and glancing toward the door before settling into conversation. She is neatly dressed, with good hygiene, but her posture is slightly hunched and guarded. During stressful topics she speaks quickly, worries aloud about \"messing things up,\" and asks for reassurance that she is not in trouble. She reports frequent stomachaches before school, difficulty relaxing at night, and a constant sense that something bad might happen to her family or at school.\n\nShe lives with her mother, younger brother, and a pet cat in a suburban apartment, and sees her father on some weekends after her parents' separation. {patientName} is a strong student who cares deeply about grades, but lately spends excessive time checking homework and becomes distressed if she thinks an answer might be wrong. She participates in choir and enjoys drawing, reading fantasy novels, and making short videos with friends, though she has recently pulled back from social events because she feels overwhelmed and worries about embarrassing herself.\n\nAt home, family members describe her as kind, responsible, and mature for her age, but also \"always on edge.\" She has trouble falling asleep because of racing thoughts and often seeks reassurance from her mother about daily routines, health concerns, and school performance. She denies substance use and is not sexually active. Her appetite is fair but inconsistent during stressful periods. She has a small but supportive friend group, although she sometimes avoids sleepovers or group outings due to anticipatory anxiety.\n\nIn the exam room, {patientName} is cooperative, makes intermittent eye contact, and answers questions thoughtfully. She describes muscle tension in her shoulders, restlessness, fatigue, poor concentration during anxious periods, and irritability at home. Despite these symptoms, she remains engaged in school and family life, and her presentation reflects a bright adolescent whose chronic, excessive worry has begun to interfere with everyday functioning."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4b8374e0-af03-4c78-bde2-5bc7395bec21",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has had excessive worry for about 10 months, gradually worsening during the current school year. She has no history of psychosis, mania, self-harm, or suicide attempts, and no prior psychiatric hospitalization. She has missed several partial school days because of anxiety-related abdominal pain and has visited her pediatrician multiple times for somatic complaints without a clear medical cause. Past medical history is notable for mild intermittent asthma and seasonal allergic rhinitis. She had an uncomplicated appendectomy in childhood.\n\nShe was born full term without major developmental concerns and has generally performed well academically. Stressors include parental separation 2 years ago and increased academic pressure since starting secondary school. Sleep is often delayed by rumination, averaging about 6 to 7 hours on school nights. She does not use alcohol, nicotine, cannabis, or other substances. Family support is present, though reassurance patterns at home may unintentionally reinforce anxiety.\n\nFunctionally, {patientName} continues attending school but with increasing procrastination, overpreparation, and avoidance of unfamiliar activities. She reports no bullying and feels physically safe at home and school. There is no known trauma history disclosed during the visit. Current symptoms are most consistent with generalized anxiety disorder after considering medical contributors and common psychiatric comorbidity such as depression."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
